# The `GCNRewritePartialRegUses.cpp` File Reference

<DoxygenPage pluginConfig={pluginConfig}>

RenameIndependentSubregs pass leaves large partially used super registers, for example: undef %0.sub4:VReg&#95;1024 = ... %0.sub5:VReg&#95;1024 = ... %0.sub6:VReg&#95;1024 = ... %0.sub7:VReg&#95;1024 = ... use %0.sub4&#95;sub5&#95;sub6&#95;sub7 use %0.sub6&#95;sub7. <a href="#details">More...</a>

## Description {#details}

RenameIndependentSubregs pass leaves large partially used super registers, for example: undef %0.sub4:VReg&#95;1024 = ... %0.sub5:VReg&#95;1024 = ... %0.sub6:VReg&#95;1024 = ... %0.sub7:VReg&#95;1024 = ... use %0.sub4&#95;sub5&#95;sub6&#95;sub7 use %0.sub6&#95;sub7.

<a href="/docs/api/classes/anonymous-namespace-gcnrewritepartialreguses-cpp-/gcnrewritepartialreguses">GCNRewritePartialRegUses</a> goes right after RenameIndependentSubregs and rewrites such partially used super registers with registers of minimal size: undef %0.sub0:VReg&#95;128 = ... %0.sub1:VReg&#95;128 = ... %0.sub2:VReg&#95;128 = ... %0.sub3:VReg&#95;128 = ... use %0.sub0&#95;sub1&#95;sub2&#95;sub3 use %0.sub2&#95;sub3

This allows to avoid subreg lanemasks tracking during register pressure calculation and creates more possibilities for the code unaware of lanemasks
